Needle Felted Ornaments

Supplies:
•Wool roving
•Felting needles
•Felting mat 
•Styrofoam ball
•Ribbon
•Scissors 

Instructions:
•Wrap white wool roving onto styrofoam ball
•Needle felt wool onto ball
•You can also use a multi needle tool
•To create the holly leaves, needle felt dark green roving into a rectangle shape
•Needle felt each long end into triangle points
•Add a bit more roving on the sides if needed to create two triangle points on either side
•Once the shape is finished add a small amount of light green roving in a line on the center on the leaf
•To create the berries roll a small amount of red roving into a ball shape and needle felt together 
•Needle felt the leaves and berries onto the ball to attach 
•To create the ornament top first cut a small piece of gray ribbon
•Fold the ribbon in half
•Wrap a small amount of gray roving around the ends of the ribbon
•Needle felt all around to bring it together
•Turn the roving as you felt to create the cylinder shape
•Needle felt the ornament top onto the ball to attach

Tag me if you try these!

See my previous reel for the holly ornament tutorial!

Supplies:
•Wool roving
•Felting needles
•Felting mat 
•Styrofoam ball
•Ribbon
•Scissors 

Instructions:
•Wrap white wool roving onto styrofoam ball
•Needle felt wool onto ball
•You can also use a multi needle tool
•To create the large poinsettia petals needle felt red roving into a triangle shape
•Needle felt the bottom two points of the triangle into rounded points to create a tear drop shape
•Once the shape is finished, needle felt a line down the middle for the veins of the petal
•Make 6 large petals
•To make the smaller petals, follow the same instructions as the large petals, but make it half the size 
•Make 6 small petals
•Roll a tiny amount of yellow roving into a ball shape and needle felt together
•Make 7 tiny balls
•Needle felt the larger petals in a circle shape onto the ball to attach
•Needle felt the smaller petals on top of the larger ones
•Needle felt some red roving into the center of the poinsettia 
•Add the small yellow balls to the center and needle felt to attach
•To create the ornament top first cut a small piece of gray ribbon
•Fold the ribbon in half
•Wrap a small amount of gray roving around the ends of the ribbon
•Needle felt all around to bring it together
•Turn the roving as you felt to create the cylinder shape
•Needle felt the ornament top onto the ball to attach

“Why does everyone want to go away? I love being home.” - Beth, Little Women

This is my favorite line from the 1994 movie. I’ve always loved being home. I love the coziness and warmth of my parent’s home. And I love spending time with my precious family.

I’ve had so many sweet memories in this home. And certain things remind me of my childhood. My girls have told me about the things that remind them of their grandparents home. The smell of a cinnamon candle burning and the sound and feel of the creaking hardwood floors. I love that when they’re older they’ll have these sweet memories. 

We all love coming home for the holidays.

A glimpse of Christmas in our home.

•The tree is a Sanibel Spruce from @balsamhill 
•The star is from @target 
•The wooden ornaments are from @burlapluxe 
•The rest of the ornaments are mostly homemade
•The greenery on the mantle is from @sticksandstonesstudio @fynandcomercantile @georgieemerson and @piperclassics. It’s a combination of two types of cedar garlands and some Norfolk pine sprays 
•The stockings are from @amazon
•The felted ball garland is from @westelm years ago
•The jingle bell garland is from @fynandcomercantile 
•The hanging bells are from @kirklands last year 
•The wooden candle pillars are from @pier1 many years ago
•The brass candlesticks are from @target last year
•The wooden tray is from @target 
•The large lantern is from @sticksandstonesstudio

Motherhood is so bittersweet. I remember years ago I would get so annoyed when older women would stop me in the grocery store and comment on my 2 under 3 and say “You’re doing a great job! Enjoy every minute, it goes by so fast.” I would think, “Yeah, well this is really hard right now and I haven’t had a decent night’s sleep in years. I’m home alone with my girls all day every day while my husband works. I never get a break.” 

Looking back now, I realize those women were probably looking at my little girls and thinking of their children at those ages. Remembering all the sweet memories with their own children and how it seems like just yesterday they were in the middle of it all. Because that’s exactly what I’m thinking when I see all of the precious little babies around me. 

Now I’m the woman in the grocery store commenting on the sweet little babies. Telling the mamas they’re doing a wonderful job and to enjoy every second because it goes by so fast. 

I wish I could go back to one of those hard days. Those days where I thought I wouldn’t make it to bedtime. I wish I could trade spots with my past self for just one day. I would soak up every single second of that day. I would snuggle my girls, read Blue Hat, Green Hat for the 1,000th time, and let them make messes. I would watch my sweet girls faces light up with each story read, kiss their soft chubby cheeks, tickle them to hear their precious little laughs, and just soak it all in. 

Motherhood is so bittersweet. It’s the most rewarding and hardest thing I’ve ever done. I am so blessed to be a mommy to my sweet girls. I’m literally living my dream come true. 

#motherhoodisbittersweet #hardisnotthesamethingasbad #motherhoodjourney #motherhoodintheraw #honestmotherhood

I typically get a lot of questions this time of year of what to do once we finish our homeschool year. Every state has different requirements for homeschoolers. We live in the state of Ohio so I‘m just sharing what we do for the end of the year. There are a couple of options for homeschoolers in Ohio, portfolio assessments or standardized testing. We’ve always done assessments. The past few years we’ve done them online and it’s been so nice to take our time with them. We had so much fun at our central Ohio @wildandfree.co book club celebration today! We read Beatrix Potter and Wind in the Willows. Every season families have a choice to read one or two books. Then we come together and discuss them. Today we played games (farmers and rabbits), made paper boats and had a boat race, enjoyed a picnic snack while discussing favorite parts of the book, and painted Peter Rabbit with watercolors in the garden. We had so much fun with our friends and can’t wait til next seasons book club! Special thanks to @amblefield and @hcgold for putting together such a wonderful day!

How do you get motivated? I haven’t been motivated to do much of anything the last few years. I’ve slowly lost all my previous desires to do things. Anything really. I’ve lost my desire to paint/ draw, keep my house organized, cook, read, share anything on social media or my blog, craft, you name it. I’ve even lost my desire to take care of myself. I rarely eat healthy or exercise anymore. I never want to go places. I always have to talk myself into going anywhere. It’s been several years since I’ve felt like myself. I’ve been able to mask it for awhile though. But I’m to the point where I can’t continue it. It’s too exhausting. I don’t want to feel this way anymore. I don’t want to be this person I’ve become. But I have no idea how to get out of it.

I made a list of all the things I want to do everyday, the person I want to be. But the list feels so daunting. And I don’t know how or where to start. I want to change, but I don’t feel like I have the motivation to actually do it. One of my biggest flaws is not following through with things. I’m terribly inconsistent. I’m so afraid to try and start these things, even if it’s just one thing, because how long will I last before I give up and stop. Usually I might last a few days, maybe a week if I’m motivated. But I’m not even motivated right now. So how do you get motivated?

Hi, I’m Sarah! I’m a homeschool mom of 2 girls, Emma, 11, and Olivia 9. We’ve been homeschooling for over 6 years. We have used My Father’s World curriculum since my oldest was in kindergarten. I started this account over 6 years ago and began sharing homeschool related tips, advice, and encouragement. It’s been so awesome to look back on all we’ve done over the years. I also have a blog, With His Grace, where I share more in depth details of our homeschool journey.

My husband and I just celebrated our 16 year anniversary! We’ve been together for over 20 years. Which is crazy to think about! He was in the Navy when we first got married and we moved around a lot. Now we live in central Ohio with our girls. 

I’m always trying to find ways to be creative. I love art, handicrafts, decorating, DIYs, organizing, and making things pretty. I love to draw portraits and paint with watercolors. I have an Etsy shop where I sell nature based learning resources from my original watercolor paintings. Although it’s been awhile since I’ve added anything new. 

I’ve been struggling a lot the past year with the realization that my girls are getting older. So I’ve tried to be more present. I haven’t shared as much on here because of it. I would love to find a balance between sharing and staying present in my girls’ lives. If you have any tips let me know!

I’ve also had difficulty finding motivation to do the things I used to love. Hence, the no new paintings in my Etsy shop. But I’m trying some things that will hopefully help bring that desire back. Again, if you have any tips let me know! 😆

I started this account to be an encouragement to other moms going through their homeschooling journey. I’ve shared a lot over the past 6 years. Sometimes I feel I’ve shared enough and there’s nothing left to share. But I’m hoping to get back into the swing of sharing here. Not just homeschool but life in general. Finding the balance of staying present and sharing will be a challenge. But I think it will help with my lack of motivation if I have a goal of sharing. I hope that you continue to enjoy following along on our journey. How long have you been following?

After sharing my girls’ bedroom this week I’ve gotten a lot of the same question. “Where are the toys?”

We have a playroom! It’s a loft above our kitchen/ living room area. It’s an open space without a door so I needed it to look somewhat put together. I’ll be sharing the details of all the storage and organization throughout the next week. 

Do you have a separate room for toys? 

#childrensplayroom #playroomideas #playroomorganization #kidsplayroom #playroomdecor #playroominspo

We love Legos and have so many in our home! My girls like to keep sets assembled so they don’t have to build them every time they want to play. I needed to figure out where to put them all though. These wall shelves from @ikeausa are deep and hold so many assembled Lego sets perfectly! The shelves are called Bersghult. We have the 31 1/2” x 11 3/4” size. The brackets are the Sanshult. 

For our loose pieces I like to separate them by color and keep them in lidded containers in a drawer. It just makes it easier to find the pieces you want. The lidded containers are called Kuggis from Ikea. For smaller pieces, people, and vehicles I like these small containers from Ikea. Although they no longer sell them.

On June 25th I started losing my hair. I noticed a small bald spot on the back left side of my head. Over the next few days I found 2 more. I had my annual exam with my obgyn that week. I mentioned it to her assuming it was hormone related. She ran some blood work to test my thyroid & other possible deficiencies. It would take about a week to get the results back. Everyday the spots seemed to get bigger. I was also noticing my hair was shedding a lot more than normal. I began to get worried & decided to see a dermatologist. They suggested more extensive blood tests to determine exactly what was going on. All of results came back “normal”. A scalp biopsy was the last determining factor. On July 12th I was diagnosed with alopecia areata, an autoimmune disease that attacks the hair follicles. Since then I’ve lost 85% of my hair. And unfortunately I’ve begun to lose some of my eyelashes & other body hair. I had no choice but to get a wig so that I could feel comfortable out in public. The wig is beautiful, but it's so hard to get used to. My dermatologist has only recommended a medication that has some serious side effects. It’s not something I want to chance. I want to get to the root of the problem, not just mask the symptom. So I’m seeing a functional medicine doctor to figure out the cause. I’m currently doing adrenal & gut testing. Hoping to get results back in the next few weeks & get a plan to reverse all of this. In the meantime I’ve already changed my diet completely. I’ve cut out all gluten, dairy, & sugar. I’m mostly just eating meat, vegetables (no nightshades), & fruits. Losing my hair has been the most traumatic experience of my life. I have been grieving for weeks. It’s driven me into a deep depression. Fear has crept in and has taken such a hold on me. It’s been hard to shake. I’m trying my hardest to speak scripture into my mind & focus on the Lord & His word. But it’s so hard. Everyday I think it will get easier but it just seems to get harder. It’s only with God’s strength & His grace that I’m able to get through each day.

Today was our first day of our 7th year homeschooling. Emma is now in 6th grade and Olivia is in 4th grade. We have always used and love My Father’s World curriculum. This year we’re using Exploration to 1850.

I always like to get my girls a little back to school gift basket on the first day. This year wasn’t too much, but they loved it anyway. They both got new water bottles with a choice of homeschooled stickers (coming soon to my Etsy shop!), a set of dual tip markers, and some colorful sticky notes. 

I also like to make something special for breakfast. Today I made  gluten free banana muffins from Simple Mills. They were delicious! We all enjoyed them! 

After breakfast the girls started with their independent work of math and lang arts. Then we moved onto Bible. This year we’re studying the book of James. And wow, what a way to start the year! “Consider it all joy, my brothers and sisters, when you encounter various trials, knowing that the testing of your faith produces endurance. And let endurance have its perfect result, so that you may be perfect and complete, lacking in nothing.” James‬ ‭1‬:‭2‬-‭4‬ Definitely a timely scripture for me! The girls and I are excited to study the book of James in depth this year. Emma said it’s her favorite book of the Bible ❤️

After Bible we did history, geography, and science. Then the girls did some independent reading. We ended our school day with lunch. I brought the bento boxes back from last year! Everyday they pick a veggie, fruit, protein, dairy, and grain. Trying to get a balanced diet in but keeping it simple. 

All in all today was a great first day back. I know it won’t always be this easy, but I’m so glad it was today. 

Have you started back to school yet?

I met with my functional medicine doctor yesterday. We talked about my adrenal & gut test results & the plan of action to fix everything. I found out I have a leaky gut, which I pretty much assumed was the case. But something I wasn’t expecting was how bad my adrenals have been. Apparently I barely produce any cortisol at all. My cortisol levels are basically flat lined at the bottom. It’s called Hypothalamic Pituitary Adrenal (HPA) Axis Dysfunction, also known as stage 3 adrenal fatigue. My body has been in a constant state of fight or flight for years which has resulted in exhaustion, depression, insomnia, hormonal imbalances, & the increase in inflammatory conditions. People in this stage find even the simplest tasks difficult to complete. He said he was shocked I have been able to function & surprised I’ve only lost my hair. He said if I let it go any longer it could get much worse. This explains SO much about what I’ve been going through the last 3 years! I feel relieved to know the cause & even better knowing it can be fixed. 

The process to reverse everything will take at least 6 months or longer. The most important thing I need to do is lower my stress levels. He told me to try not to “do all the things”, learn to say no, don’t be so hard on myself, ask for help, & take time for myself everyday. I also need to get adequate sleep. I haven’t had a good nights sleep since June. It’s an awful feeling to feel exhausted all the time but not be able to sleep. 

We also talked about the supplements I will be taking & my nutrition plan. He doesn’t want me to go on a strict diet like AIP that will cause additional stress on my body. My diet will be loosely paleo, but not strict. The main thing is for me to eat more & not stress about food. I just need to eat nourishing foods & stay away from gluten & most grains. 

I know it’s going to be a long process, but I am hopeful it will work. I just need to keep my mind focused & not be too hard on myself. Especially if I don’t see results right away.
